listd64.doc

Written by Martin Sigley, GroundhoGrafix 3/28/2026.

Documentation for the listd64 utility. Compiled with tcc (Tiny C Compiler), it also
compiles with gcc but the executable is considerably larger.

HOW TO USE THE UTILITY:
This is a .D64 disk image directory listing program. You can use it on the command 
line like this:

listd64 mydisk.d64

It accepts multiple files at once or a single file. Wildcard input is not supported
from the console, however under windows GUI you can select as many D64 images as you 
like and drop them on to listd64.exe and it will extract all of the directories in to
the dir.lst file as well as print them to the screen. If you drag and drop from a
different folder than where listd64 is then look for the dir.lst file in the folder
where your D64 images came from.

HOW TO USE THE CODE:

To use in your own C programs:

byte is a new data type. It is the same as unsigned char.

You have to include the header file:
#include "listd64.h"


Your first function call should be d64Init():

d64Init();


Then declare a D64Image* variable:

D64Image* d.


Load the D64 image: 

d = d64LoadImage("mydisk.d64").


You can then access any track or block on the disk image using the function d64tba()
like this, which stands for D64 Track, Block to Address:

unsigned address;
address = d64tba(18,1). 

You can then read from the loaded image file like this:

*(d->image + d64tba(18,1))

Here is an example of printing an entire block/sector to the screen:

for(byt=0; byt<256; byt++)
	printf("%2d ", *(d->image + d64tba(18,0) + byt));
	
d64tba() is used just to locate the beginning of a specific track and block, you will
have to add an additional offset between 0 - 255 to actually read through that block.
Remember the first 2 bytes of every block are the track and sector of the next block
in the chain. If the track (1st byte) is 0 then then this is the last block in the
chain and the block (2nd byte) tells you how many bytes are used inside this last
block.
	
When finished with the disk image it is a good practice to deallocate the memory
used for it by calling:

d64UnloadImage(d);


EXTRAS:
There is a 256 byte array in the listd64.h file called pc2asc[]. pc2asc means Power C
to ASCII. You can use this to convert PETSCII to ASCII like this:

char c;

for(byt=0; byt<256; byt++)
{
	c = pc2asc[*(d->image + d64tba(18,0) + byt)];
	putchar(c);
}

This example is the just of it but is pretty worthless in it's current form. Likely
you will hunt down a track and block on the disk using d64tba() and locate a PETSCII
string that you'll want to use pc2asc[] on to convert that string to a modern ASCII
string.

Use D64Header to place a structure overlay on top of the header block. First make a
pointer like so:

D64Header *h;
D64Image* d;

Then assign the header pointer to the block like this:

h = (D64header*) (d->image + d64tba(18,0));

you can then read the different parts of the header using the struct members. Refer
to the listd64.h file for all of the members. If unsure of the what the member
represents refer online or in your 1541 User's Manual near the end of the manual for
a break down of each section.

you can now get a piece of header data like this:

byte b = h->dosVersion;

For file entries you can do the same as we did with the D64Header except you'll
use d64tba(18,1) and point the D64FileEntry pointer there. There will be 8 file
entries per block so you can reference them like this after you assign the pointer.

D64FileEntry *fe = (D64FileEntry*) (d->image + d64tba(18,1));

byte nextTrack = fe[0].track;
byte nextBlock = fe[0].block;

Here we find the first character of the file name for the 3rd file in the block:

putchar(fe[2].fileName[0]);

Even better yet we could have done this:

putchar(pc2asc[fe[2].fileName[0]]);

That would not only get the first letter of the filename but would also convert it
from PETSCII to ASCII and print it.

Essentially, d64LoadImage() and d64tba() will give you access to all data on a D64
image. You can read all of the data on the image. If you wanted to change the data
all you would have to do is create a function to resave the image to disk like this.

D64Image* d;
File *fptr;

d = d64LoadImage("original.d64");
fptr = fopen("newdisk.d64", "w");
fwrite(d->image, sizeof(byte), d->size, fptr);

Now your changes are saved to "newdisk.d64".

Hope this document helps get you started. Happy Commodoring!